Investigators at international bodies like the United Nations and the International Criminal Court are harvesting, cataloging, and analyzing millions of photos, posts, and videos from social media in an effort to hold human rights abusers accountable in court. pic.twitter.com/ySa6HrCABJ

This is a huge shift. Investigators documenting abuses used to depend heavily on diaries, records, and interviews with witnesses that sometimes took place years after the fact. Now, the evidence is available immediately — sometimes uploaded by militants incriminating themselves.

The Treasury Department refused to explain why its officials were communicating with unofficial Gmail accounts at the same time as Russia was sending the suspicious requests, or to tell BuzzFeed News whether it eventually turned over any documents in response.

It was not the only time that concerns about serious counterintelligence threats were raised at FinCEN during the past two years. At least 10 employees have filed formal whistleblower complaints about the department. Some of FinCEN’s top officials quit in anger.

The extraordinary departure from protocol is latest evidence of widespread dysfunction at FinCEN, the Treasury Department’s elite financial watchdog, which a two-year BuzzFeed News investigation has laid bare.

Insiders warned the backchannel exposed the Treasury to potential hackers because the Russian messages contained attachments — a common way for intruders to worm their way inside an organization’s servers.

Internal whistleblowers warned Treasury staffers that Russia could be trawling for sensitive financial records — including Social Security and bank account numbers — to spy on, endanger, or recruit targets in the West. But staffers continued using the Gmail backchannel into 2017.

Russian agents sought info on the Ziff brothers, billionaire investors who had run afoul of the Kremlin.  Weeks later, at the now notorious Trump Tower meeting, a Russian lawyer offered Trump aides “dirt” on Hillary Clinton, including her supposed connection to the Ziff brothers.

During the presidential campaign, as the Kremlin meddled in the election, Treasury officials were using their government email accounts to exchange messages with a network of private Hotmail and Gmail accounts set up by Russians.
Russian agents used backchannel communications to press US officials for private financial documents on at least two dozen dissidents, academics, private investigators, and American citizens.

As the far right continues to gain ground, the left finally looks like it’s trying to fight back. But will Varoufakis’ movement be enough? Read @jlfeder’s profile of a man trying to save Europe’s left. https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/lesterfeder/yanis-varoufakis-unite-europe-left-right-wing-steve-bannon?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

Europe’s volatility and the growing threat of the far right does create an opening for new players to galvanize the left. But Varoufakis is not the only one trying to play the role of savior.  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/lesterfeder/yanis-varoufakis-unite-europe-left-right-wing-steve-bannon?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

His mission is also to energize the left around a common agenda. While the US has exported Breitbart, which boosted Brexit, the kind of progressive surge that launched politicians like Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez has yet to take hold across Europe.

Varoufakis is traveling across Europe — and doing events with Bernie Sanders in Vermont — to promote a new transcontinental political party to save the EU by enacting a “Green New Deal” that he says will spread prosperity and tackle global warming. pic.twitter.com/BxylpWaw77

Why is the left so divided? For one thing, the very questions that are forging a natural alliance among the far right — immigration, identity, and national sovereignty — split the left, in many cases driving a wedge right down the middle of existing parties.

In the midsts of this, Varoufakis is trying to solve a central problem: As the right has united, the left dissolved. Many of the continent’s major center-left parties, perhaps because they offer no alternative to the reigning political order, sit on the edge of extinction.

The populists are gaining ground, fast. Look at the numbers on the board: • Far-right parties lead the government in Italy.  • They form the largest opposition faction in Germany’s parliament. • Hungary is inching closer to dictatorship by the day.  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/lesterfeder/yanis-varoufakis-unite-europe-left-right-wing-steve-bannon?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

Remember Yanis Varoufakis, the motorcycle-driving former Greek finance minister? He rose to fame during Europe’s financial crisis for opposing budget cuts to pay off bad loans.   Now, he’s styling himself as the Bernie Sanders of Europe, trying to give the left a new identity. pic.twitter.com/MGA1bRMqQR

The past decade has seen the rise of the far-right everywhere from the US to India to Brazil. In Europe, fringe factions started winning elections. Meanwhile, Europe's left-wing parties are on life support.  Does Europe's left finally have a hero? Decades later, many of Jensen’s victims are still coming to terms with what they endured, and want justice from the authority figures who failed to protect them.  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/tylerkingkade/miles-city-james-jensen-fred-anderson-larry-nassar?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc … pic.twitter.com/DVHRNn34ZS

When news of the lawsuit broke, the district said it was “shocked.” But a 1997 letter to Jensen from school officials shows he was ordered to stop giving “body rub downs” to boys unsupervised, stop inviting boys to spend nights at his home, and end his “Mentorship Program.”

Though a document shows the school knew 20 years ago that something was amiss, Jensen was never reported to authorities. He’s lived alongside many of his victims in Miles City, Montana— where the county attorney says Jensen often searched for porn involving young boys.

Many victims are wracked with guilt for having recruited close friends and relatives into the Program only to find out they were later abused. Most have never even told their parents, spouses, or children what happened to them in high school.

Jensen was arrested and charged with 10 counts of child porn, but the statute of limitations will keep him from ever being prosecuted for abusing students.   In Miles City, to say the school district screwed up is to say friends and neighbors failed to stop a child molester.

Jensen’s abuse happened in plain sight. Parents knew their kids went to his house multiple times a week. Various coaches sent boys to him to get full-body massages after football and wrestling practice, even when some boys objected.

Everyone had to be recruited into the Program, either by another student already in it or by Jensen, who portrayed it as an elite club, according to the lawsuit filed by victims. Lawyers for the victims believe Jensen abused as many as 200 boys in the 1990s.

Ikuenobe’s journey into slavery was shaped not just by conflict or poverty in Africa, but also directly by Europe’s policies on migration. Yet, at a time when this practice of modern day slavery is at a crisis level, few know anything about it. https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/monicamark/slavery-nigeria-libya?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

Fewer migrants are making it to Europe. More are dying, disappearing, or being abused — except since it’s no longer happening on the shores of Europe, it rarely appears on the news.   Meanwhile, in the US, President Donald Trump called reports of slaves in Libya “fake news.”

But it’s much harder to make it to Europe now. As debates rage about the morality of the EU’s “stop the boats” policy, its darkest consequences were often erased from the narrative: the tens of thousands of black Africans entrapped in a growing slave market.

What do we mean when we say victims “sell themselves into slavery?” Let’s unpack that. Thousands of desperate people arrive in Libya in hopes of making it across the Mediterranean, in search of a better life in Europe. Some give up the last of their savings for this. pic.twitter.com/FjnYvMYNoX

Ikuenobe wasn’t willing to risk everything to get to Europe — he just thought slavery was a thing confined to the history books. So when he gave up his savings of 800,000 naira ($2,200), the last thing on his mind was that he would be tortured, then sold.   https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/monicamark/slavery-nigeria-libya?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc … pic.twitter.com/O806jeFYrz

Some experts have argued that in a country like Libya, where chaos reigns, such treatment doesn’t amount to slavery. Their argument overlooks the reality of who ends up being treated this way: pic.twitter.com/UP6ZaED897

Our reporter talked to Jude Ikuenobe, who left his home in Nigeria hoping to make that journey to Europe. Instead, he spent more than two years trying to survive in the underbelly of modern-day slavery. His story is harrowing. pic.twitter.com/gAFgx75mCb

The viral video was just the tip of the iceberg of a forced labor market worth $150 billion worldwide. Soon after, videos emerged of Libyan coast guards whipping terrified black women and children at sea. So we followed this story.

Last year, a shocking video obtained by CNN went viral. In it, a group of sub-Saharan Africans were being auctioned as slaves somewhere in Libya. Offscreen, a slave trader emphasized the strength of the black men for sale. The men were sold for $400 each. https://edition.cnn.com/2017/11/14/africa/libya-migrant-auctions/index.html …

.@nickswicks has been investigating a universe where tens of thousands are detained indefinitely, spend years working without pay, and are at constant risk of being kidnapped, sold, and auctioned from one militia to another. https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/monicamark/slavery-nigeria-libya?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

But Ford is not the norm, and other efforts give a glimpse into the private aftermath of sexual assault.  One seeks funds for a woman’s abortion after her rape. Another woman asks for help with her phone bill, explaining she was diagnosed with PTSD and out of work after her rape.

Most famously, a campaign for Christine Blasey Ford raised $647,610 to help cover her family’s security, transportation, and temporary relocation costs — far more than the $150,000 goal, with leftover funds being donated to organizations helping survivors. https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/remysmidt/christine-blasey-ford-donating-extra-money?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

A search for “rape” on GoFundMe yields about 4,000 campaigns, while “sexual harassment” turns up nearly 500.  Many fundraisers have been created by the victims themselves, or in their names by loved ones.

"Time's Up" has raised more than $22 million for victims, making it GoFundMe's biggest campaign ever.  But crowdfunding has also highlighted the financial toll rape and sexual harassment can take — and many fundraisers are not nearly as successful.   https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/jtes/gofundme-timesup-metoo-fundraising-record?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

The first allegation against Tyson came from Tchiya Amet, who says he raped her while they were graduate students at the University of Texas at Austin in the 1980s.  Tyson denied the allegation, noted her “odd” interests in New Age healing, and suggested she had a “false memory."

All three of these women say that Tyson’s behavior toward them was not simply inappropriate or clumsy; it was harassment.   Their stories, they said, which all took place in professional settings, show a clear abuse of power  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/azeenghorayshi/neil-degrasse-tyson-sexual-allegations-four-women?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

A third woman, Katelyn Allers, an astronomy and physics professor at Bucknell University, alleges Tyson grabbed her and reached down the front of her dress to look at her tattoo at a scientific meeting in 2009  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/azeenghorayshi/neil-degrasse-tyson-sexual-allegations-four-women?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

Ashley Watson, Tyson’s ex-driver and "Cosmos" assistant, says he invited her to his place, after which he took her by the shoulders and said, “I want to hug you so bad right now, but I know that if I do, I’ll just want more.”   Two days later, she resigned  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/azeenghorayshi/neil-degrasse-tyson-sexual-allegations-four-women?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

After taking time off school and seeking therapy, Abigail is starting to get back to her old life. But she’s still angry. And Ward is still free, reportedly at another college.  “Now he’s someone else’s problem,” Abigail said. “It’s just like kicking the can down the road.”

For Abigail, the verdict, and legal process that took up a year of her life, has made things worse.   After his victory in court, Freeman, the defense attorney, mocked Abigail’s experience on social media as “regret sex by a Becky.” Ward’s campus ban expired after 12 months.
“We need a fundamental sense of consent to know what nonconsensual sex means,” says Joyce Short, and advocate against rape by fraud. “You change morality when you change the laws.”

Ward’s attorney says his client could have been prosecuted for sexual battery, though that would have only covered the initial moment that Ward groped Abigail when she was asleep, not the sex when she woke up. It also carried a maximum prison sentence of 2.5 years.

Versions of rape by fraud laws exist in only a handful of US jurisdictions, including California, Missouri, and Puerto Rico.  After Abigail’s case, there’s been a push from US lawmakers, as well as sexual assault activists, to criminalize rape by fraud and better define consent. pic.twitter.com/KhgwJMefgq

Abigail’s case has exposed a loophole in the laws of not just Indiana, but more than three-quarters of US states and territories: The word consent, when it does appear in a statute, is not expressly defined in laws. pic.twitter.com/aLsgLFf3La

In Indiana, sex only becomes rape when it’s compelled through force or threats, if the victim is mentally disabled and can’t properly consent, or if he or she is unaware that the sex is occurring.  Abigail knew she was having sex. She just didn’t know it was with Ward. pic.twitter.com/ySwVoL5P6b

During Ward’s three-day trial, defense attorney Kirk Freeman argued that while his client’s conduct was “ungentlemanly” it wasn’t illegal under Indiana law.   The jury agreed. pic.twitter.com/KhwGIzJXxV

After realizing what had happened in February 2017, Abigail went to the hospital that night, where nurses took swabs for a rape kit.   Donald Grant Ward, 19, confirmed Abigail’s story to police, and was charged with two counts of rape.

His death could produce a chilling effect on those who want to speak out against abuse by the clergy. Other nuns who supported their sister after she accused the bishop of rape have said they are afraid for their lives since Kuriakose’s death. pic.twitter.com/Zhuy87CRUs

Kuriakose was the lone priest to break ranks with the church and testify against the bishop. Taking a brave stance in supporting the nun, he could have bolstered her case by his further testimony in court.

This year, four priests from a southern state in India have been accused of sex crimes. But the case of Bishop Franco Mulakkal is the biggest of all — he’s the man accused of raping the nun, and he became the first Indian bishop to ever be arrested. pic.twitter.com/wYhSavxH7E

In India, there are 20 million Catholics, out of 28 million Christians — the third-largest religious group after Hindus and Muslims.   Victims of sexual abuse have found it almost impossible to get their allegations taken seriously, let alone bring them before a court.

The story connects to a global context: the Catholic Church has been beset by sex abuse crimes in recent years. The last decade has seen the Vatican move from insisting other religions are just “as rife with abuse” to the pope condemning these crimes and “begging forgiveness.”

That’s because Kuriakose was a key witness in a case in which a powerful bishop has been accused of raping a nun. The case is tearing India’s Catholic Church apart. https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/india-catholic-church-bishop-mulakkal-father-kuriakose …

When Father Kuriakose Kattuthara was found dead, it was on a school day. By the time police arrived, the body was already moved to the morgue.   Many fear that one of the biggest scandals to hit the Catholic Church in India will be buried with the priest.  https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/india-catholic-church-bishop-mulakkal-father-kuriakose …

Experts say cutting trees and clearing undergrowth around homes, however, makes sense, as does making homes more fire-resistant.  “This is a home ignition problem much more than a wildland management problem." https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/peteraldhous/logging-forest-california-wildfires?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

The circumstances of California's worst fires don’t suggest that forest thinning would have helped much.   The Woolsey fire, which just devastated Malibu, and the Thomas fire, which raged around Santa Barbara at the end of 2017, both burned through scrubland, not forests.

Across the West as a whole, however, there’s little hard evidence that thinning forests will do much to reduce damaging wildfires.  That hasn’t stopped state, federal, and environmental groups from coming together to thin California’s forests in an attempt to reduce fire risks.

In drawing attention to forest management, Trump has tapped into a contentious scientific debate: Can the American West’s growing problems with wildfire be solved, in part, by thinning overgrown forests? pic.twitter.com/ID4YmZNC8x

Nondisclosure agreements are common in the tech industry. Whether government officials beholden to the public interest should be signing NDAs with corporations is now being called into question thanks to Amazon, Foxconn, Google, and other big tech companies.

“They tell us that’s what we’re here for, that we’re whores, that they’ll treat us as badly as they want to,” a sex worker named Monica said. “They have all the money. You can’t really fight that.”   https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/johnstanton/metoo-men-escaping-mexico-sex-workers-hookerfucker1?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …

The sense of freedom has emboldened some men. The sex workers BuzzFeed News spoke to said they’re routinely beaten, choked and spit on by clients. But police know these men fuel Tijuana’s economy, and are reluctant to arrest Americans who might take their money and never return.

“They say they’re more free here than over there,” a 24-year-old sex worker named Laura said of her American “friends,” the term most sex workers here use to refer to clients. “They say that just by looking at a woman, you can get sued. They call it harassment.”

In Mexico, sex workers are feeling the effects of the #MeToo backlash from angry American men as the workers encounter US customers who are bitter that their gender no longer gives them unchallenged dominion over women back home.

It’s one of the harsh realities of #MeToo that border cities provide an escape for the very men the movement sought to enlighten. They may be hearing the message, but it’s easier to ignore down here, where entire families of women toil in a sex industry aimed at Americans.
“You can go to a strip club, call an escort agency, or hit up a massage parlor. It's an easy, prepackaged sex destination,” the client said.

“It's not safe to hit on women in the US anymore,” a Tijuana brothel client said. In Mexico “slapping a strippers ass is not only ok, but encouraged! In the US you'd get kicked out of the club, prosecuted for harassment, fired from your job, and probably listed as a sex offender”

For some American men, Mexico’s legal sex work industry makes hiring escorts as easy as booking a massage. But lately, they say Mexico offers not only convenience, but also a safe haven from the implications of #MeToo.   https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/johnstanton/metoo-men-escaping-mexico-sex-workers-hookerfucker1?bftwnews&utm_term=4ldqpgc#4ldqpgc …
